result.execSummary:
The defendant Nathaniel J Watt was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Armed Robbery [Modifiers: Party to a Crime], a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.32(2).
  • Drive or Operate Vehicle w/o Consent, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.23(3).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Nathaniel J Watt in court with attorney Thomas W. Kurzynski.  Defendant Nathaniel J Watt in custody.  Jay Randal Pucek appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

Case set for sentencing hearing. State placed negotiations on the record. Victim Impact Statement received and filed. Court finds the State has complied with the victim rights legislation. Statements made as to sentencing. Additional statements made by Kendale N.

As to COUNT 1- 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 12 YEARS, concurrent to COUNT 2, concurrent to 14CF5603, with credit for 240 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 6 YEARS; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 6 YEARS.  

As to COUNT 2- 
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 3 YEARS, concurrent to COUNT 1, concurrent to 14CF5603, with credit for 240 days time served; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1 YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS. 

Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program. The defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.

Court costs, fees, surcharges and restitution be paid through collection by the department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.

Defendant Nathaniel J Watt in court with attorney Thomas W. Kurzynski.  Defendant Nathaniel J Watt in custody.  Jay Randal Pucek appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Negotiations placed on the record. Pursuant to plea negotiations and on motion of the State, Court ordered Count 3 dismissed and read-in to case for the purposes of sentencing. Defendant sworn in.  

As to Counts 1 and 2:  Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis for the plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the Information and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored. Specifically to Count 1, the Court advised the defendant that he may never posess body armor.

Case is adjourned for sentencing in Branch 20.   All parties are notified that effective August 3, 2015 case will be reassigned to Branch 25, Judge Stephanie Rothstein, in Room G55A of the Criminal Justice Facility.  Sentencing hearing scheduled for August 12, 2015 at 01:30 pm.
